{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599599"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:57:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:57:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15585"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15585"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.18,0.45,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70377"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8276"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55841"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"},{"type":"tags","id":"10113"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19992"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner for routine health screening. She feels well with no specific symptoms. Thyroid function tests are ordered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory patterns would be most consistent with subclinical hypothyroidism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High thyroid stimulating hormone with normal free thyroxine","Low thyroid stimulating hormone with normal free thyroxine","Normal thyroid stimulating hormone with low free thyroxine","High thyroid stimulating hormone with low free thyroxine","Normal thyroid stimulating hormone with normal free thyroxine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESubclinical hypothyroidism is characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) with normal free thyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E levels. This represents early thyroid dysfunction where the pituitary is increasing TSH production to maintain normal thyroid hormone levels through compensatory mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect patterns can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow TSH with normal free thyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E indicates subclinical hyperthyroidism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal TSH with low free thyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E is not physiologically possible due to negative feedback mechanisms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh TSH with low free thyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E indicates overt hypothyroidism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal TSH with normal free thyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E indicates normal thyroid function\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH is the most sensitive indicator of thyroid dysfunction due to the logarithmic relationship between TSH and free thyroid hormones in the negative feedback loop. Small changes in free thyroxine result in large changes in TSH secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Subclinical hypothyroidism is defined by elevated thyroid stimulating hormone with normal free thyroxine levels","The negative feedback loop between thyroid hormones and thyroid stimulating hormone makes TSH the most sensitive marker of thyroid dysfunction","Subclinical hypothyroidism often represents early thyroid failure and may progress to overt hypothyroidism"],"references":["Chaker L, Bianco AC, Jonklaas J, Peeters RP. Hypothyroidism. Lancet. 2017 Sep 23;390(10101):1550-1562. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(17)30703-1. Epub 2017 Mar 20. PMID: 28336049; PMCID: PMC6619426","Patil N, Rehman A, Anastasopoulou C, et al. Hypothyroidism. [Updated 2024 Feb 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519536/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55841"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15585"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55841"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T20:10:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T20:11:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8276"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70377"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici